I think you need to do this, as you need only the `number` between those `slashes`.

    while (m.find()) {
        System.out.println(m.group(2));
    }

**group(0)** - gives the whole match `(/n/)`

**group(1)** - gives you the first slash `(/)`

**group(2)** - gives you the number `(n)`

**group(3)** - gives you the second slash `(/)`

If you want only the number to be printed use `m.group(2)`.

    System.out.println(m.group(2));

Another solution is to use [lookahead and lookbehind][1]


    Pattern p = Pattern.compile(&quot;(?&lt;=\\/)(\\d+)(?=\\/)&quot;);
    Matcher m = p.matcher(&quot;A/8/E/5/F/6/G/7/H&quot;);
    while (m.find()) {
    	System.out.println(m.group(0));
    }


  [1]: http://www.regular-expressions.info/lookaround.html

You must use `group(i)` to extract the i-th thing in brackets (excluding non-capturing groups).

`group(0)` or `group()` is the whole pattern.

So, for your example, you need `group(2)`.

Also note your code won&#39;t work on `8/5/4/3` since `8` can&#39;t match because it doesn&#39;t have a `/` before it, `4` can&#39;t match because `5` used the `/` in between and `3` can&#39;t match because it doesn&#39;t have a `/` after it. You need to include check for start of string (`^`) for `8` and end of string (`$`) for `3` and use look-ahead `(?=...)` for `4`.

I also used a non-capturing group `(?:...)`, so you can use `group(1)` instead of `group(2)` (this is the only difference `(?:...)` makes).

Also, you don&#39;t need to escape `/`.

Final code:

    Pattern p = Pattern.compile(&quot;(?:^|/)(\\d+)(?=/|$)&quot;);
    Matcher m = p.matcher(&quot;8/5/4/3&quot;);
    while (m.find()) {
        System.out.println(m.group(1));
    }

[Regular expression reference](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/regex/Pattern.html).

